# Design Workflow (Paper)

How design tasks on the Paper canvas are run. Discipline first: respect the
exact scope the user gives.

## Scope

- Build only the element the user scoped. If they say "the card", design the
  card — not a surrounding shell, dashboard, nav, or demo frame.
- If surrounding context would genuinely help review, propose it in one line
  and wait. Never build unrequested scaffolding preemptively.

## Artboards

- A component gets its own artboard sized to the component
  (`height: "fit-content"`, width to match the component), not a faux device
  frame.
- Use full device frames (e.g. 1440×900) only when the user asks for a full
  screen or page.

## Direction before building

- Matching the existing yyork system: skip the formal brief, state the
  direction in one line, then start.
- Net-new or exploratory work: post a short brief (mood, palette, type) and
  wait for explicit approval before any canvas mutation.

## Iteration

- Build the first pass, screenshot it, then stop and hand back for review. Do
  not run multiple self-invented polish iterations before the user weighs in.

## Variants

- Default to one option. Produce 2–3 directions only when variants are
  requested.

## Fidelity

- Default to matching existing tokens and components exactly (Geist, neutral
  tokens, square corners, dense tool aesthetic). Diverge only when told to
  explore.

## Handoff to code

- Stay in Paper. Translate a design into the codebase only when explicitly
  asked.
